INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_2035_L006$$, 2027, $$(Note: Gross/Weapon System Unit Cost is a function of Infantry Squad Vehicle (ISV), Infantry Squad Vehicle- Utility (ISV-U), and Infantry Squad Vehicle-Heavy (ISV-H) quantities and unit cost.)

 The Infantry Squad Vehicle (ISV) composed of the ISV and ISV-Utility (ISV-U) is a modified commercial off the shelf (M-COTS) program which incorporates greater affordability goals, as well as requirements for
 reduced weight, and increased vehicle transportability. The ISV provides enhanced tactical mobility for an Brigade Combat Team (BCT), a nine-Soldier infantry squad, with their associated equipment to move
 quickly around the battlefield. This includes the ability to execute medium distance insertion operations which provides commanders greater freedom of movement and freedom of action. The ISV-U is a five-
 seat ground vehicle platform that leverages the base ISV configuration. This provides the US Army with a highly mobile and transportable platform that provides Rapid Mission Payload capability on the proven
 ISV platform. The ISV-H is a six-seat ground vehicle platform that supports the BCT with enhanced operational flexibility by enabling air assault missions, mission command on the move and Tactical Operations
 Center (TOC) operations while providing increased payload capacity and power management capabilities to adapt to dynamic battle conditions. ISV deploys worldwide by sea, air, and land modes to support
 strategic deployment and operational maneuver in accordance with Army and Joint doctrine. This capability provides flexibility for entry operations (permissive and non-permissive) to counter threat anti-access
 strategies by using multiple austere entry points to bring in combined arms configured units.

 ISV, transportable by CH-47/UH-60, air drop capable, payload of nine Soldiers with equipment/supplies for three days of operations. The purpose of the ISV-U is to serve as cargo variant of the ISV passenger
 for BCTs and other end Users with larger payload. The intended function is to provide larger payload capacity and payload area for unique mission packages in the cargo bed across a battlefield for the User to
 achieve their objective. The Infantry Squad Vehicle - Heavy (ISV-H) is designed to fulfill critical operational roles such as export power for TOC operations and onboard power for Mission Command on the Move.
 These roles emphasize versatility, mobility, and support for tactical operations across diverse environments. Primary intended usage for the ISV-H is at Division and Brigade.

 The Prior Years and FY 2025 quantity listed on the P-40 are not accurate. The correct total quantities should be Prior Years: 1,953, and FY 2025: 1,997. The correct quantities for Prior Year and FY 2025 are
 reflected on the P-5.

 The approved Army Procurement Objective (APO) for ISV and ISV-U is 11,582 and the Army Acquisition Objective (AAO) for ISV is 11,582. Breakout as follow: ISV : 4,677 & ISV U: 6,905

 The approved Army Procurement Objective (APO) for ISV-H is 606 and the Army Acquisition Objective (AAO) for ISV-H is 606.$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Army                                                                                                                      Date: April 2026
