 Description:
 This funding line is directly aligned to the Army Assured Positioning, Navigation and Timing modernization priority.

 The Assured Positioning, Navigation and Timing (APNT) capability provides Army ground maneuver forces access to Military Code (M-Code) and assured PNT in accordance with National Defense Authorization
 Act guidance under conditions where Global Positioning Systems (GPS) may be limited or denied (jammed and spoofed). APNT products are ruggedized tactical systems that enable Army forces the ability to
 shoot, move, communicate, thereby allowing forces to maneuver from operational and strategic distances to close with, destroy, and exploit the enemy with sufficient combat power, tempo, and momentum.
 APNT addresses two critical capability gaps: Access and Integrity. Access is the ability to retrieve accurate PNT information in a contested Electronic Warfare/Cyber environment. Integrity is the ability to trust
 the PNT information. PNT is a critical enabler of many Army Maneuver, Fires, Intelligence, Mission Command and communications that are dependent on accurate Position and Timing, and a foundational
 Multi-Domain Battle capability to support: calibrated force posture (position and maneuver across strategic distances); multi-domain formations (operate in contested spaces against near-peer adversaries);
 convergence (continuous integration of capabilities in all domains).

 Approved Requirements: The Alternative Navigation (ALTNAV) Abbreviated Capabilities Development Document (A-CDD) on 29 August 2022; the Dismounted APNT System (DAPS) Capabilities Development
 Document (CDD) on 28 January 2022; the Mounted APNT System (MAPS) CDD on 12 September 2020. MAPS and DAPS are implementing Congressional and OSW guidance to develop and field Military Code
 (M-Code) Global Positioning System (GPS) Ground user Equipment.

 Assured PNT consists of:

 K49010 - SSN K49010 has no funds requested in FY 2027. Mounted/Dismounted Receiver: Deploys Resiliency and Software Assurance Measures (RSAM) to legacy Selective Availability and Anti-Spoof Module
 (SAASM) based military Global Positioning System (GPS) receivers, including Defense Advanced GPS Receiver (DAGR) and embedded Ground Based - GPS Receiver Applications Module (GB-GRAM) to
 recognize, reject, and report bad navigation data until more effective PNT solutions are deployed.

 K49020 - Dismounted Hub: The Dismounted Assured PNT (APNT) System (DAPS) is an enduring capability that meets Congressional (10 USC 2281) and Department of War guidance to develop and field
 Military Code (M-Code) Global Positioning System (GPS) to dismounted Soldiers, Commanders, and applicable End User Devices to provide assured timing and position data necessary to effectively engage
 targets, share data across the network, and conduct mission command functions. DAPS delivers APNT in an optimized form factor that supports dismounted mission profiles in denied environments. The DAPS
 enables the Dismounted Soldier with APNT capabilities critical to the targeting process for precision fires, command and control, and maneuver for selected Army units. DAPS were evaluated through Operational


