INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_2035_L106$$, 2026, $$Funding has been realigned out of this line to support the Army's Next Generation Command and Control (NGC2) initiative.

 B29810 Army Command Post Integrated Infrastructure (CPI2) in FY 2027 and beyond was realigned to PE B11400/B11411 Command and Control (C2) Infrastructure, C2 Compute Infrastructure, as part of the
 new funding structure for the Next Generation Command and Control (NGC2) investment to modernize C2 systems for the Infrastructure Layer.

 Effective with the 11 Feb 2025 Acquisition Decision Memorandum (ADM), Command Post Integrated Infrastructure (CPI2) was renamed to Command Post Modernization (CPMod).

 CPMod (B29801) is aligned to and supports the Army Next Generation Command Control (NGC2) initiative to modernize Command and Control (C2) systems, Infrastructure layer. This funding is to accelerate
 divestment of legacy equipment.

 The Next Generation Command and Control (NGC2) is a top modernization priority for the U.S. Army, aimed at transforming how we communicate, coordinate, and operate across the battlefield. Command Post
 Modernization (CPMod) plays a foundational role in this transformation by delivering the infrastructure that connects tactical communications, data systems, and applications into a cohesive ecosystem. CPMod
 enables rapid integration of emerging technologies and modular upgrades-ensuring the Army can outpace threats remain operationally flexible in contested environments. Without CPMod the Army cannot
 execute the infrastructure layer to support the NGC2 architecture.

 The B29801 funding line is a strategic investment by the Army to procure tactical edge compute (TEC) and store hardware and integration efforts. Lessons learned at Project Convergence Capstone 5 (PCC5)
 have significantly increased the demand for On The Move (OTM) capability and distributed command and control nodes. Army recognizes a need to leverage technology enabling resilient and intuitive command
 posts. TEC provides the Army a distributable, common compute and store solution capable of hosting Next Generation Command and Control (NGC2) applications in a modular, configurable hardware package.
 TEC delivery will move Army Command and Control capabilities away from costly and complex separate "stove-piped boxes" with individual applications, reducing training and sustainment costs associated with
 multiple unique HW installation requirements. The use of open standards will make it simpler and more cost-effective to upgrade capabilities and/or keep pace with commercial technology by eliminating complex
 integration challenges and proprietary interfaces. Integration will address up to 20 unique NGC2 enabling technologies across multiple vehicle platform type/variants within Army units.$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Army                                                                                                                     Date: April 2026
Appropriation / Budget Activity / Budget Sub Activity:                                                                  P-1 Line Item Number / Title:
