INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_3010_L048$$, 2026, $$The F-15 is a versatile 4th-generation fighter aircraft and is central to Combatant Commanders' ability to fulfill National Defense requirements (Joint Lethality in Contested Environments) for numerous operational
 plans (OPLANS) and contingency plans (CONPLANS) in near-peer conflicts. The proliferation of 4th generation enemy aircraft, sophisticated "double-digit" anti-aircraft missile systems, and other threat systems
 pose a significant threat to F-15 survivability.

 The F-15 Eagle Passive Active Warning Survivability System (EPAWSS) ensures future F-15 viability, and replaces the legacy, functionally-obsolete F-15 Tactical Electronic Warfare System (TEWS). F-15
 EPAWSS is an integrated and digital electronic warfare suite which includes electronic detection and identification, geolocation, electronic countermeasures (jamming), and countermeasures dispensing (chaff/
 flares). EPAWSS will significantly improve the F-15's ability to deny, degrade, deceive, disrupt, and defeat Radio Frequency (RF) and electro-optical / infrared threat systems within contested and highly contested
 environments.

 Core Candidate Decision (CCD), dated 10 May 2013, and Depot Source of Repair (DSOR) #13-077F, dated 8 July 2016 and updated 8 August 2023, approved and assigned Warner-Robins Air Logistics
 Complex as the site for organic repair of F-15 EPAWSS hardware and software.

 QUANTITY & INSTALLATION INFORMATION:

 -The Air Force will equip 99 F-15E aircraft with EPAWSS production hardware. Prior-year's funding supports 94 production shipsets, and 2 Group B retrofit hardware kits (to retrofit the 5 test aircraft initially
 modified during development; modification will be done organically during Programmed Depot Maintenance), leaving 3 partial Group B retrofit hardware kits to be procured in subsequent years.

 -All kits were procured with prior year funding, enabling the Air Force to maximize opportunities for organic installations at Warner Robins Air Logistics Complex (WR-ALC), in parallel with installations at the
 Contractor Modification Facility (CMF) (reference P-3a Installation Information).

 -FY 2024+ funding requested for F-15E EPAWSS installations were aligned to the annual induction schedule to avoid early-to-need funding caused by installation delays (a shift from previous requests which
 funded contractor installations by procurement lot). Resulting from previous delays, prior-year funding accounts for contractor installs into FY 2026.

 -FY 2026 funding will support 15 installation starts planned for FY 2026 (2 of 8 CMF installs and all 13 organic installs).

 Milestone/Development Status$$, NULL, $${"bucket":"fy26_specific_pb_v43","method":"direct_li_with_title_overlap","rapidfuzz_score":100.0,"src_li":48,"src_title":"F-15 EPAW","supersedes":"fy26_pointing_at_fy27_pb_placeholder","applied_at":"2026-05-09T_v196b"}$$, $$Budget J-Books/FY26/USAF/FY26 Air Force Aircraft Procurement Vol II.pdf$$, 425, 425, $$5ea94b05c3754f50$$, $$2026-05-10T04:05:58.829571+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_3010_L055$$, 2027, $$This line item funds modifications to nine (9) C-37A and seven (7) C-37B aircraft, equivalent to commercial Gulfstream 5 and Gulfstream 550 aircraft. The C-37A/B is a twin-engine jet transport designed to
 transport high-ranking United States government officials worldwide. The designed service life for C-37A is 40,000 hours (average of 24,740 hours remaining). The designed service life for C-37B is 40,000 hours
 (average of 31,293 hours remaining for our 3 legacy and 37,246 hours remaining for 4 new aircraft). As the fleet nears the service life limits, additional evaluations are made for continued service.

 Service bulletins and low cost modifications are necessary for continuing Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) certification while improving flight safety, reliability, and maintainability.

 This funding may include, but is not limited to, emerging modification requirements to support Program Support Costs (PSC), Advisory & Assistance Services (A&AS), systems integration lab, trainers, equipment,
 other government costs, and Senior Leader Communications System modernization efforts.

 Funding may be used to address Diminishing Manufacturing Sources (DMS) issues.

 Funding for this exhibit is contained in PE 0401314F.

 Justification:
 No FY 2027 funding requested.$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Air Force                                                                                                                Date: April 2026
